        </div>
        These shadow art pieces are designed with a spherical outer shell and inner extrusions which block light casted into them to create a scene much like shadow puppets would. The design of these are on going and work is being done to make them as visually appealing as well as optimized for 3D printing as possible.
        <br>
        Here are some example of scenes that could be put into the center instead of the "star gazing" scene. These are also in development and may change. Below you can use the included toggle to switch the lights on and off on this specific shadow orb!
        <figure>
          <img class="w3-image" src="/static/shadow_orb/example_off.png" alt="" id="orb_interactive">
          <figcaption>
            <br>
            <button class="w3-button cm-button" onclick="orbInteract()" style="width:50%;"> Toggle lighting </button>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <hr>

        <div class="cm-h1 w3-xxxlarge w3-center">
          Artistic Items Pedestal
        </div>
        <div class="cm-h1 w3-large">
          The goal of this pedestal was to help showcase the shadow orb by providing a place to hang the orb from.
        </div>
        The designs for the pedestals first began as a brainstorming session. This was when ideas for display objects were still very new so both the pedestals and the display object concepts evolved together. The goal was to integrate the display as much as possible with the objects themselves. Below are some pictures of that process.<br> <br>
        <button class="w3-button cm-button" onclick="expand('design')">Design process</button>
        <br>
        <div id="design" class="w3-container w3-round-large cm-acordian w3-hide">
          <img class="w3-image" src="/static/pedestals/sketch1.png" alt=""> <br>
          <img class="w3-image" src="/static/pedestals/sketch2.jpg" alt=""> <br>
          <img class="w3-image" src="/static/pedestals/sketch3.jpg" alt=""> <br>
          <img class="w3-image" src="/static/pedestals/sketch3.jpg" alt=""> <br>
          To help narrow down the options from the first sketch to the final, a survey was sent out. Using the data gathered from the conjoint survey, the five most-liked designs were determined. These top five designs were then included in a subsequent survey which sought to test a user's visual interest in each pedestal and willingness to approach it. This subsequent survey shows that the pedestal in the top left corner of the last image ranked highest in all categories. Below is a render of what that may look like. <br>
          <figure>
            <img class="w3-image" src="/static/pedestals/render.png" alt="ohh nooo">
            <figcaption>The most popular pedestal.</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
